<h2>John Doyle</h2> 
 
<img src="../../../icons2/vntop.gif"/> 

<p class="bc"> 
[<a href ="../../../index.html">Victorian Web Home</a> —> 
<a href="../../index.html">Visual Arts</a> —> 
<a href="../index.html">Illustration</a>]</p>

</div> 
<div id="main"> 

<p class="lq">... there is no doubt Doyle’s work is a sort of bridge between the anarchic rudeness of the eighteenth century and the development of ‘good taste’ and ‘gentlemanliness’ in the Victorian ‘age of improvement.’ <a href ="../../../authors/wmt/index.html">W. M. Thackeray</a> thought the humour too restrained, an emollient only good enough to raise a smile but rarely a laugh (19); nevertheless, H. B. defined a  new direction for graphic satire that was taken up by the cartoonists of <a href="../../../periodicals/punch/index.html"><span class="periodical">Punch</span></a>, the situational comedy of <a href="../leech/index.html">John Leech</a> and <a href="../tenniel/index.html">John Tenniel</a>, and in the droll, wistful reflections of his more famous son, “Dicky” Doyle. — Simon Cooke</p>
 
 <a href="3.html"><img src="3.jpg" height="180" class="floatright"/></a>
 
